{"title_page": "Korean Air Flight 801", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = Korean Air Flight 801\n| image = Korean Airlines flight 801 crash site.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.1\n| alt = \n| caption = Korean Air flight 801 crash site\n| occurrence_type = Accident\n| date = {{Start date|1997|08|06}}\n| summary = [[Controlled flight into terrain]] due to [[pilot error]], insufficient training and [[Pilot fatigue|fatigue]]\n| site = [[Nimitz Hill]], [[Asan, Guam|Asan]], [[Guam]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|13|27|19|N|144|43|58|E|region:GU_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Boeing 747|Boeing 747-3B5]]\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[Korean Air]]\n| tail_number = [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19970806-0 HL7468]\n| origin = [[Gimpo International Airport|Kimpo International Airport]]\n| stopover = \n| stopover0 = \n| last_stopover = \n| destination = [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]]\n| passengers = 237\n| crew = 17\n| fatalities = 229{{efn|name=\"fatality footnote\"|This figure includes a 229th fatality that occurred on October 10th, more than 30 days after the accident. The NTSB however classifies them as a survivor with \"serious\" injuries in accordance with regulations.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|1}}}}\n| injuries = 25\n| missing = \n| survivors = 25 (Initially 26)\n| IATA = KE801\n| ICAO = KAL801\n| callsign = KOREAN AIR 801\n| occupants = 254\n}}\n'''Korean Air Flight 801''' (KE801, KAL801) was a scheduled international passenger flight operated by [[Korean Air]]. The flight crashed on August 6, 1997, on approach to [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]], in the [[United States]] territory of [[Guam]], killing 229{{efn|name=\"fatality footnote\"}} of the 254 people aboard. The aircraft crashed on [[Nimitz Hill]] in [[Asan, Guam|Asan]], [[Guam]], while on approach to the airport.<ref name=\"GuamHome\">{{Cite web|url=http://ns.gov.gu/guam/indexmain.html|title=Korean Air Flt 801 - Official Guam Crash Site Information Web Center|website=ns.gov.gu|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref> The [[NTSB|National Transportation Safety Board]] cites poor communication between the flight crew as probable cause for the crash, along with the captain\u2019s poor decision making on the [[Instrument approach|non-precision approach]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Reports/AAR0001.pdf|title=Controlled Flight Into Terrain Korean Air Flight 801 Boeing 747-300, HL7468 Nimitz Hill, Guam August 6, 1997|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2000|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board|location=Washington D.C.|id=NTSB/AAR-00/01|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Aircraft and crew ==\n\n=== Aircraft ===\n[[File:Boeing 747-3B5, Korean Air AN0610287.jpg|thumb|right|The aircraft involved in the accident, HL7468, taxiing at Paris Charles de Gaulle Airport in 1985]]\nFlight 801 was normally flown by an [[Airbus A300]]; since [[Korean Air]] had scheduled the August 5\u20136 flight to transport Chamorro athletes to the [[Pacific Games|South Pacific Mini Games]] in [[American Samoa]],<ref name=\"Transcripts\">\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/transcripts.html Transcripts Between Guam Airport Tower and KA801 before Crash].\" ''Government of [[Guam]]''. Retrieved on August 30, 2010.</ref> the airline designated HL7468, a 12-year-old [[Boeing 747|Boeing 747-300]] delivered to Korean Air on December 12, 1984,<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|16,28}} to fly the route that night.<ref name=\"Transcripts\" /><ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/indexmain.html Official Guam Crash Site Center \u2013 Korean Air Flt 801],\" ''Government of Guam''</ref>\n\n=== Crew ===\nThe flight was under the command of 42-year-old Captain Park Yong-chul ([[Hangul|Korean]]: \ubc15\uc6a9\ucca0, [[Hanja]]: \u6734\u93de\u5586, [[Revised Romanization of Korean|RR]]: ''Bak Yong-cheol''. [[McCune-Reischauer|M-R]]: ''Pak Yongch'\u014fl'')<ref>\"[http://starbulletin.com/98/03/25/news/story1.html Two Systems Down in KAL 801 Crash],\" ''[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]''</ref> The captain had close to 9,000 hours of flight time (3,192 of them on the Boeing 747) and had recently received a Flight Safety Award for negotiating a 747 engine failure at low altitude.<ref name=\"Mayday Final Approach\" /> Park had originally been scheduled to fly to [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]; since he did not have enough rest for the Dubai trip, he was reassigned to Flight 801.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|3,15}}  The first officer was 40-year-old Song Kyung-ho ([[Hangul|Korean]]: \uc1a1\uacbd\ud638, [[Hanja]]: \u5b8b\u6176\u660a, RR: ''Song Gyeong-ho'', M-R: ''Song Ky\u014fngho''), who had more than 4,000 hours' flying experience (including 1,560 hours on the Boeing 747), and the flight engineer was 57-year-old Nam Suk-hoon ([[Hangul|Korean]]: \ub0a8\uc11d\ud6c8, [[Hanja]]: \u5357\u932b\u85b0, RR: ''Nam Seok-hun'', M-R: ''Nam S\u014fkhun''),<ref>\"[https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/542233.pdf DOCKET NO.: SA-517 EXHIBIT NO. 2F].\" ''ntsb.gov'' [[National Transportation Safety Board]]</ref> a veteran pilot with more than 13,000 flight hours, including 1,573 hours on the Boeing 747.\n\n==Accident==\n[[File:Guam2.ogv|thumb|NTSB animation of Flight 801's descent]]\n[[File:KAL801QT3.ogv|thumb|NTSB animation of Flight 801's descent, showing the aircraft's distance from the runway]] \n[[File:Korean Air Flight 801 crash, Guam air traffic control recording (August 1997).oga|thumb|ATC traffic after KAL 801 failed to land at the airport]]{{Expand section|date=November 2019}}\nFlight 801 departed from Seoul-Kimpo International Airport (now [[Gimpo Airport|Gimpo International Airport]]) at 8:53&nbsp;p.m. (9:53&nbsp;p.m. Guam time) on August 5 on its way to Guam. It carried three flight crew members (the two pilots and the flight engineer), 14 flight attendants, and 237 passengers from 4 countries,<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|11,23}} a total of 254 people. Of the passengers, three were children between the ages of 2 and 12 and three were 24 months old or younger.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|45,57}} Six of the passengers were Korean Air flight attendants, who were [[deadheading (employee)|deadheading]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|3,15}}\n\nThe flight experienced some turbulence but was uneventful until shortly after 1:00&nbsp;a.m. on August 6, as the jet was preparing to land. There was heavy rain at Guam so visibility was significantly reduced and the crew attempted an instrument landing. The [[glideslope]] Instrument Landing System (ILS) for runway 6L was out of service; Captain Park believed it was in service, however, and at 1:35 am managed to pick up a signal that was later identified to be from an irrelevant electronic device on the ground.  The crew noticed that the aircraft was descending very steeply, and noted several times that the airport \"is not in sight.\" Despite protests from flight engineer Nam that the detected signal was not the glide-slope indicator, Park pressed on. The crew lowered the landing gear and continued to prepare the aircraft for landing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/09/us/in-asiana-crash-investigation-early-focus-is-on-the-crews-actions.html|title=In Asiana Crash Investigation, Early Focus Is on the Crew\u2019s Actions|last=Wald|first=Matthew L.|date=2013-07-08|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-07-22|last2=Onishi|first2=Norimitsu|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> 12 seconds before impact, the Ground Proximity Warning system activated, warning the crew about their actual altitude. First officer Song declared a missed approach, and captain Park declared a go-around, but it was too late. At 1:42 am, the aircraft's main landing gear struck a fuel pipeline, and crashed into Nimitz Hill near Asan, Guam. The crash site was about {{convert|3|nmi|mi km}} short of the runway, at an altitude of {{convert|660|ft}}.\n\nOf the 254 people on board, 229 died as a result of the crash. One survivor, 36-year-old Hyun Seong Hong<!--Hong is an American, so put in Western order--> (\ud64d\ud604\uc131, also spelled ''Hong Hyun Sung'') of the United States, occupied Seat 3B in first class, and said that the crash occurred so quickly that the passengers \"had no time to scream\"<ref name=\"PilotErrorNYT\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/08/world/pilot-error-is-suspected-in-crash-on-guam.html|title=Pilot Error Is Suspected in Crash on Guam|last=Pollack|first=Andrew|date=1997-08-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and likened the crash to \"a scene from a film.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|45}}<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19970808/ai_n14123263 Anger and tears as Guam crash families beg to see dead] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216075715/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19970808/ai_n14123263 |date=December 16, 2008 }}, ''[[The Independent]]''</ref>\n\n== Rescue ==\n[[Image:Korean Air Flight 801 wreckage.jpg|thumb|Wreckage of HL7468 burns at the Sasa Valley crash site.]]\nThe rescue effort was hampered by the weather, terrain, and other problems. Emergency vehicles could not approach due to the fuel pipeline destroyed by the crash and blocking the narrow road. [[United States Navy]] Seabees of NMCB133 were some of the first on the scene as they utilized their earth moving equipment to clear roadways and timber from the crash site approach. The Seabees used backhoes to crack open the still-burning plane to rescue survivors and erected mortuary tents for first responders. There was confusion over the administration of the effort; the crash occurred on land owned by the [[United States Navy]] but civil authorities initially claimed authority. The hull had disintegrated, and [[jet fuel]] in the wing tanks had sparked a fire that was still burning eight hours after impact.\n\n===Rika Matsuda===\n\nGovernor [[Carl T.C. Gutierrez]] found 11-year-old Rika Matsuda, from [[Japan]], who boarded the flight with her mother, 44-year-old Shigeko.<ref name=\"Honeymoon\">\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/honeymoon-flight-that-ended-in-horror-1244140.html Honeymoon flight that ended in horror].\" ''[[The Independent]]''. Thursday August 7, 1997. Retrieved on August 30, 2010.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-61001878 Jet hell Rika's scars will last forever.],\" ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]''</ref> They were heading to Guam on vacation. Rika Matsuda described what happened to her and her mother to interpreters.<ref name=\"PilotErrorNYT\"/> Shigeko could not free herself from the aircraft and told Rika to run away. Luggage piled on the girl and her mother as the crash occurred; Rika Matsuda said her mother, unable to free herself, asked her to leave.<ref name=\"PilotErrorNYT\"/> Shigeko died in the fire. After escaping from the aircraft, Rika discovered a surviving [[flight attendant]], Lee Yong Ho (\uc774\uc6a9\ud638). They stayed together until Gutierrez discovered them.<ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/miracle/ Korean Air Survivor \u2013 Rika's Miracle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126062957/http://ns.gov.gu/guam/miracle/ |date=2007-11-26 }},\" ''Government of Guam''</ref> Rika Matsuda, treated at Guam Memorial Hospital in [[Tamuning, Guam|Tamuning]], was released on August 7, 1997, and was reunited with her father, Tatsuo Matsuda. The two were then escorted to the Governor House where they were the guests of Gutierrez and the [[First Lady of Guam]], Geri Gutierrez, for several days; afterwards Rika and Tatsuo Matsuda flew to Japan.<ref name=\"GuamHome\"/><ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/miracle/ Korean Air Survivor \u2013 Rika's Miracle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126062957/http://ns.gov.gu/guam/miracle/ |date=2007-11-26 }}.\" ''Government of Guam''. Retrieved on February 13, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Investigation and probable cause==\n\nA special weather observation made at 01:32 ten minutes before the impact reported:\n\n<blockquote>Wind 090\u00b0 at 6 knots; visibility\u20147 miles; present weather\u2014shower vicinity; sky condition\u2014scattered 1,600 feet, broken 2,500 feet, overcast 5,000 feet [above ground level]; temperature\u201427\u00b0 C; dew point\u201425\u00b0 C; altimeter setting 29.85 inches Hg; remarks\u2014showers vicinity northwest-northeast.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|20}} </blockquote>\n\nAnother special weather observation made at 01:47 five minutes after the impact reported:\n\n<blockquote>Wind variable at 4 knots; visibility\u20145 miles; present weather\u2014light rain shower; sky condition\u2014few 1,500 feet, scattered 2,500 feet, overcast 4,000 feet; temperature 26\u00b0 C; dew point 24\u00b0 C; altimeter 29.85 inches Hg.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|21}} </blockquote>\n\nThe U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) investigation report stated that a contributing factor was that the ATC [[Minimum Safe Altitude Warning]] (MSAW) system at Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport had been deliberately modified so as to limit spurious alarms and could not detect an approaching aircraft that was below minimum safe altitude.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|175}} The probable cause of the accident was the captain's poor execution of the [[Instrument approach|non-precision approach]],<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|175}} the captain's fatigue, poor communication between the flight crew, and Korean Air's lack of flight crew training.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|175}} The crew had been using an outdated flight map that was missing a 724 foot obstruction symbol depicted at the NIMITZ VOR and that map stated the Minimum Safe Altitude while crossing the NIMITZ VOR for a landing aircraft was {{convert|1300|ft}} as opposed to the updated altitude of {{convert|1440|ft}}.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|36}} Flight 801 crashed near the NIMITZ VOR, which is situated on Nimitz Hill at a height of {{convert|680|ft}} at 1:42 am, when it descended below the minimum safe altitude of {{convert|1440|ft}} during its landing approach. The report also identified that the captain may have mistakenly believed that the airplane was closer to the airport\nthan it was and that there may have been confusion about the location of the [[Distance Measuring Equipment]] (DME) in relation to the airport, with the crew anticipating the VOR/DME to be located at the airport. The DME was sited at the NIMITZ VOR some {{Convert|3.3|nmi|mi km|abbr=on}} from the airport and such a configuration had not been part of Korean Air's simulator training, the crew's training for such non-precision approaches having been carried out in scenarios where the DME was located at the airport. Nevertheless the correct DME distances were shown on the approach chart.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|144}}\n\nThe NTSB presented its findings on March 24, 25 and 26, 1998 in the [[Hawaii Convention Center]] in [[Honolulu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/67326.pdf|title=Public Hearing in Connection with the Investigation of Aircraft Accident Korean Air Flight 801, B-747-300 Agana, Guam August 6, 1997 - Transcript 1|date=March 24, 1998|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board}}</ref><ref name=\"pubhearing\">{{cite web|url=https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/67328.pdf|title=Public Hearing in Connection with the Investigation of Aircraft Accident Korean Air Flight 801, B-747-300 Agana, Guam August 6, 1997 - Transcript 2|date=March 25, 1998|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108060020/http://www.ntsb.gov/events/kal801/trans_980325.htm|archivedate=January 8, 2007|url-status=}}</ref><ref name=\"pubhearingg\">{{cite web|url=https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/67210.pdf|title=Public Hearing in Connection with the Investigation of Aircraft Accident Korean Air Flight 801, B-747-300 Agana, Guam August 6, 1997 - Transcript 3|date=March 26, 1998|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070109090647/http://www.ntsb.gov/events/kal801/trans_980326.htm|archivedate=January 9, 2007|url-status=}}</ref>\n\nThe section of the report entitled \"Probable Cause\" concluded:\n\n<blockquote>The National Transportation Safety Board determines that the probable cause of this accident was the captain\u2019s failure to adequately brief and execute the non-precision approach and the first officer\u2019s and flight engineer\u2019s failure to effectively monitor and cross-check the captain\u2019s execution of the approach.  Contributing to these failures were the captain\u2019s fatigue and Korean Air\u2019s inadequate flight crew training.\n\nContributing to the accident was the Federal Aviation Administration\u2019s intentional inhibition of the [[MSAW|minimum safe altitude warning system]] at Guam and the agency\u2019s failure to adequately manage the system.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|xi,175}}</blockquote>\n\n==Passengers==\n[[File:KoreanAir801Survivorloc.JPG|thumb|Locations of the survivors ([[:File:KoreanAir801Survivorloc EN.svg|Greyscale version for colorblind persons]])]]\n\n===Deaths and injuries===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" \n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n!rowspan=2|Nationality||colspan=2|Passengers||colspan=2|Crew||colspan=2|Total\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n!Total||Killed||Total||Killed||Total||Killed\n|- valign=top\n|South Korea||style=\"text-align:center;\" |218||style=\"text-align:center;\" |201|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |17||style=\"text-align:center;\" |14||style=\"text-align:center;\" |235||style=\"text-align:center;\" |215\n|- valign=top\n|New Zealand||style=\"text-align:center;\" |1||style=\"text-align:center;\" |0||{{n/a|-}}||{{n/a|-}}||style=\"text-align:center;\" |1||style=\"text-align:center;\" |0\n|- valign=top\n|United States||style=\"text-align:center;\" |13||style=\"text-align:center;\" |10||{{n/a|-}}||{{n/a|-}}||style=\"text-align:center;\" |13||style=\"text-align:center;\" |10\n|- valign=top\n|Japan||style=\"text-align:center;\" |5||style=\"text-align:center;\" |4||{{n/a|-}}||{{n/a|-}}||style=\"text-align:center;\" |5||style=\"text-align:center;\" |4\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|'''Total'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''237'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''215'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''17'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''14'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''254'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''229'''\n|}\n\nOf the 254 people on board, 223 \u2013 209 passengers and 14 crew members (all 3 flight crew and 11 cabin crew) \u2013 were killed at the crash site.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|45,57}}\n\nOf the 31 occupants found alive by rescue crews, two died en route to the hospital and a further three in hospital.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|3,15,45,57}} Among the survivors, 16 received burn injuries. The 26 survivors were initially treated at [[Guam Memorial Hospital]] (GMH) in [[Tamuning, Guam|Tamuning]] or at the U.S. Naval Hospital in [[Agana Heights, Guam|Agana Heights]]. Four were subsequently transferred to the U.S. Army Burn Center in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], [[Texas]].<ref name=\"GuamHome\"/><ref>\"[http://www.burncarerehab.com/pt/re/jburncr/abstract.01253092-200609000-00014.htm;jsessionid=LFjQcWfxBHX8YNpbJy95J2vMdcLZfTgyjpvz0bJbf6Jdxf35XTxz!-1004083789!181195629!8091!-1 Airplane Crash in Guam, August 6, 1997: The Aeromedical Evacuation Response].\"</ref> and eight to University Hospital in Seoul. On October 10 the same year, one passengers died of their injuries, bringing the amount of fatalities to 229 and the amount of survivors to 25.<ref>\"[http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=41097 One Crash Victim Dies, Three Cling to Life at Burn Center].\" ''U.S. Department of Defense''.</ref><ref>Wiechmann, Lori. \"[http://www.onlineathens.com/1997/081297/0812.korean.html Last member of Atlanta family on downed Korean jet dies]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\" ''[[Athens Daily News]]''. August 12, 1997. Retrieved on July 1, 2011.</ref><ref>\"[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970902&slug=2558056 Daily Briefing].\" ''[[The Seattle Times]]''. Tuesday September 2, 1997. Corrected on September 8, 1997. \"Two more people who initially survived last month's crash of a Korean Air jumbo jet in Guam have died, bringing the death toll to 228, a South Korean foreign ministry spokesman said today. Korean flight attendant Han Kyu-hee died on Saturday at Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio, Texas. Another South Korean, Jung Young-hak, a passenger, died on Sunday in the same facility.\"</ref><ref>Gillert, Douglas J. \"[http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=41097 One Crash Victim Dies, Three Cling to Life at Burn Center].\" [[U.S. Department of Defense]]. Retrieved on June 30, 2011. \"The other victims brought here were Se Jin Ju, 28; Kyu Hee Han, 29; and Young Hak Jung, 39, all South Korean citizens. Along with Chung, they were the most severely burned survivors and needed the kind of treatment the Brooke Army Medical Center burn unit here provides.\"</ref><ref>\"[https://www.ntsb.gov/safety/safety-recs/recletters/A00_19_20.pdf Safety Recommendation Date:  January 27, 2000 In reply refer to:  A-00-19 and  -20].\" [[National Transportation Safety Board]]. Retrieved on June 30, 2011. \" A passenger with serious injuries died at the U.S. Army Medical Center in San Antonio, Texas, on October 10, 1997, but is not officially listed as a fatality because the passenger\u2019s death occurred more than 30 days after the accident\"</ref>\n\nThere were 22 passengers and three flight attendants who survived the crash with serious injuries.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|11,23,45,57}}<!-- This includes the person who died in October -->\n\n===Notable passengers===\n[[Shin Ki-ha]], a four-term South Korean parliamentarian and former leader of the [[National Congress for New Politics]], traveled with his wife and around 20 party members. Shin and his wife were killed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/05/guam.late/ |title=Guam |accessdate=March 6, 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050306010328/http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/05/guam.late/ |archivedate=March 6, 2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage-9801E1DC173CF934A3575BC0A961958260.html|title=For Relatives Of Victims, Anger Adds To Anguish|last=Gargan|first=Edward A.|date=August 7, 1997|website=|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nJang Se-jun, a South Korean voice actor, was also on board the flight with his wife. Both died in the accident.\n\n===Identification and repatriation of bodies===\n\nOn August 13, 1997, 12 sets of remains were brought to Guam's airport to be readied to be flown back to Seoul. Clifford Guzman, a governor's aide, said that two of the 12 were taken back to the morgue. Of the 10, one was misidentified and had to be switched before takeoff. The 10 bodies transported to Seoul were of seven passengers and three female flight attendants. On the same date, an NTSB family affairs official named Matthew Furman said that in total, by that date, 46 bodies had been identified.<ref name=\"Seattletimes\">\"[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970813&slug=2554557 Guam Crash Aftermath Upsets Kin].\" ''[[The Seattle Times]]''. August 13, 1997.</ref>\n\n==After the crash==\n[[File:KALMemorialAsanGuam.jpg|thumb|Korean Air Flight 801 Memorial in [[Asan, Guam]]]]\nAfter the crash occurred, the airline provided several flights for around 300 relatives so that they could go to the crash site.<ref>Coleman, Joe. \"[http://archives.savannahnow.com/sav_pdf_archive/text/fr852/A_2474131.pdf Survivors recount the fiery last moments] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324173658/http://archives.savannahnow.com/sav_pdf_archive/text/fr852/A_2474131.pdf |date=2012-03-24 }}.\" ''[[The Associated Press]]'' at the ''[[Savannah Morning News]]''. Thursday August 7, 1997. 10A. Retrieved on July 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn August 13, 1997, 50 protesters staged a sit-in at Guam Airport, saying that the recovery of the dead was taking too long; they sat on blankets and sheets of paper at the Korean Air counter.<ref name=\"Seattletimes\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nOn August 5, 1998, the first anniversary of the crash, a black [[marble]] [[obelisk]] was unveiled on the crash site as a memorial to the victims.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nAfter the accident, Korean Air services to Guam were suspended for more than four years, leading to reduced tourist spending in Guam and reduced revenues for Korean Air.<ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/specifics.html Specifics of Crash Site Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216081618/http://ns.gov.gu/guam/specifics.html |date=2008-12-16 }}.\" ''Guam Government''. Retrieved on December 9, 2008.</ref> When Seoul-Guam services resumed in December 2001,<ref>\"[http://archives.starbulletin.com/2001/12/28/business/story3.html Korean Air resumes service to Guam for the first time in 4 years].\" ''[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]''. Friday December 28, 2001. Retrieved on April 29, 2009.</ref> the flight number was changed to 805. The flight number for its Seoul-Guam route is now 111 and operates out of [[Incheon Airport|Incheon]] instead of Gimpo, using a [[Boeing 777-300]] or an [[Airbus A330]].\n\nIn 2000, a lawsuit was settled in the amount of $70,000,000 [[United States dollar]]s on behalf of 54 families against the airline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speiserkrause.com/cases/|title=Our Work and Past Cases|website=speiserkrause.com|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNew Zealander Barry Small, a helicopter pilot and a survivor of the accident, lobbied for safer storage of duty-free alcohol and redesigns of crossbars on airline seats; he said that the storage of duty-free alcohol on Flight 801 contributed to spreading of the fire and the crossbars injured passengers to the point where they could not escape from the aircraft (Small himself was injured when he broke his leg on one of the crossbars during the crash, but was still able to escape the aircraft).<ref name=\"Mayday Final Approach\" /><ref>\"[https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/67313.pdf Exhibit 16C \u2013 Korean Air Flight 801].\" [[National Transportation Safety Board]]. Retrieved on June 26, 2009.</ref><!--The NTSB recorded Barry Small's testimony about the alcohol-->\n\nThe Government of Guam moved its website about the Korean Air crash after the Spamcop program alerted the government that [[advance fee fraud]] spam from Nigeria used the website link as a part of the scam.<ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/ This webpage has been cancelled.]\"{{sic}} <!--Please do not correct to \"canceled\"-->''Government of Guam''. Retrieved on April 29, 2009.</ref> Scam e-mails used names of passengers, such as Sean Burke, as part of the fraud.<ref>Larson, Aaron. \"[https://www.expertlaw.com/library/consumer/spam_email_fraud3.html False Promises of Inheritance \u2013 Spam Email Fraud].\" ''Law Offices of Aaron Larson'' at ExpertLaw. July 2004. Retrieved on May 13, 2009.</ref>\n\nFollowing the Korean Air 801 crash, it was brought to the [[NTSB]]'s attention that foreign carriers flying in and out of the US were not covered by the Aviation Disaster Family Assistance Act of 1996 and Korean Air did not have a plan to deal with the situation they encountered. As a result, [[US Congress]] passed the Foreign Air Carrier Family Support Act of 1997 to require those carriers to file family assistance plans and fulfill the same family support requirements as domestic airlines. Not only does the Act ensure that all victims and family members will be treated equitably, regardless of the carrier they use, it also impels many carriers that may not have thought about family assistance issues to give them due consideration in their emergency response plans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/news/speeches/JimHall/Pages/Remarks_before_the_International_Symposium_on_Family_Victim_Assistance_for_Transportation_Disasters_Arlington_Virginia.aspx|title=Remarks before the International Symposium on Family & Victim Assistance for Transportation Disasters, Arlington, Virginia|date=September 28, 1998|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*[[Malcolm Gladwell]] discusses the crash in the context of cultural effects on power structures in his book ''[[Outliers (book)|Outliers]]''.<ref>Outliers ch 7, The Ethnic Theory of Plane Crashes, pp 209\u2013223</ref>\n*The [[Discovery Channel Canada]] / [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] TV series ''[[Mayday (Canadian TV series)|Mayday]]'' (also called ''Air Crash Investigation'' or ''Air Emergency'') dramatized the accident in a 2007 episode titled ''Final Approach'', although it was also titled ''Missed Approach'' for the episode on ''Air Disasters''.,<ref name=\"Mayday Final Approach\">{{Cite episode|title=Final Approach|series=[[Mayday (Canadian TV series)|Mayday]]|network=[[Discovery Channel Canada]] / [[National Geographic Channel]]|season=4|year=2007|episode-link=|series-link=|date=|number=|url=http://www.discoverycivilization.ca/shows/episodedetails.aspx?eid=581&sid=568|access-date=June 26, 2009}}{{dead link|date=December 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> and \"Blind Landing\" for the UK.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|South Korea|United States|Aviation|1990s}}\n* [[Impact of culture on aviation safety]]\n* [[Avianca Flight 011]]\n* [[American Airlines Flight 965]]\n* [[Air Inter Flight 148]]\n* [[Air New Zealand Flight 901]]\n* [[Asiana Airlines Flight 733]]\n* [[Crew resource management]]\n* [[Ground proximity warning system]] (GPWS)\n* [[List of accidents and incidents involving commercial aircraft]]\n* [[Prinair Flight 277]]\n* [[Colgan Air Flight 3407]]\n* [[List of aviation accidents and incidents involving CFIT]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n*[[National Transportation Safety Board]] [http://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Reports/AAR0001.pdf Korean Air Flight 801 Final Accident Report]\n\n'''Further reading'''\n*[[Politics of Guam|Government of Guam]]: [http://ns.gov.gu/guam/indexmain.html Guam Crash Site Center \u2013 Korean Air Flight 801], photographs, passenger manifest, scanned news articles, and related links\n* [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] ''[[Newshour with Jim Lehrer]]'': \"[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/transportation/july-dec97/koreanair_8-6.html Tragedy on Guam],\" August 6, 1997\n* \"[http://edition.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/06/guam.passenger.list/ List of passengers aboard Korean Air Flight 801]\" (also lists crew members)  ''[[CNN]]''\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE6DE173CF934A3575BC0A961958260  Airline's List Of Survivors],\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. August 7, 1997.\n* Pollack, Andrew. \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D02EEDC153CF93BA3575BC0A961958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all Pilot Error Is Suspected in Crash on Guam],\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. August 8, 1997.\n*[http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/06/guam/ Guam rescuers: 27 survivors, no more expected], ''[[CNN]]'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/06/guam/ Archive])\n* [http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/08/korea.air.crash/index.html Pilot error focus in Guam crash], ''[[CNN]]''\n*[http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/09/guam.crash/ Photos used to identify Guam crash victims], ''[[CNN]]'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/09/guam.crash/ Archive])\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950CE6DC173CF934A3575BC0A961958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print  29 Survive the Guam Crash, but Hope for Others Ends], ''[[The New York Times]]''\n*[http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/05/guam.later/ Rescuers search smoldering jet debris in Guam], ''[[CNN]]'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/05/guam.later/ Archive])\n* [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/transportation/july-dec97/koreanair_8-6.html Tragedy on Guam], ''[[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]''\n\n==External links==\n{{ external media\n| align  = right\n| width  = \n| image1 = [http://www.airliners.net/search?registrationActual=HL7468&display=detail Photos of HL7468 at Airliners.net]}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikisource|Korean Air Flight 801 investigation}}\n*\"[https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Pages/AAR0001.aspx Korean Air Flight 801].\" ([http://www.ntsb.gov/publictn/2000/AAR0001.htm Alternate]) ([https://web.archive.org/web/20061211043023/http://www.ntsb.gov/publictn/2000/AAR0001.htm Archive]) \u2013 [[National Transportation Safety Board]]\n*[http://www.tailstrike.com/060897.htm Cockpit Voice Recorder transcript and accident summary]\n* Hosenball, Mark and Watson, Russell. \"[http://www.newsweek.com/id/96244/output/print Fly The Risky Skies].\" ''[[Newsweek]]''. August 18, 1997.\n* Wald, Matthew L. \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A00E1D91138F936A15750C0A96E958260 Tape Shows Crew's Confusion in Guam Crash].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. March 25, 1998.\n* \"[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0UBT/is_45_13/ai_57439972 Safety Board Cites Crew, Carrier, Controller, and Regulatory Authorities' Lapses in Guam Crash].\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20081216075700/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0UBT/is_45_13/ai_57439972 Archive]) ''[[Air Safety Week]]''. November 8, 1999.\n* \"[http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE1DA103CF933A2575BC0A961958260 Families Try to Identify Bodies in Korean Crash].\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20081216102310/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE1DA103CF933A2575BC0A961958260 Archive]) ''[[The New York Times]]''. August 10, 1997.<!--At that date no bodies had been identified. Investigators showed photos of bodies to relatives so they can help ID bodies-->\n*{{Cite web|url=http://ns.gov.gu/guam/|title=Official Guam Crash Site Center|last=|first=|date=|website=ns.gov.gu|access-date=November 11, 2004|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19980109201212/http://ns.gov.gu/guam/|archive-date=January 9, 1998|df=mdy-all}}\n{{Aviation incidents and accidents in 1997}}\n{{Korean Air}}\n\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents involving controlled flight into terrain]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents caused by weather]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents caused by pilot error]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1997]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Boeing 747]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents in Guam]]\n[[Category:Korean Air accidents and incidents|801]]\n[[Category:South Korea\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:1997 in Guam]]\n[[Category:1997 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:August 1997 events in Oceania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = Korean Air Flight 801\n| image = Korean Airlines flight 801 crash site.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.1\n| alt = \n| caption = Korean Air flight 801 crash site\n| occurrence_type = Accident\n| date = {{Start date|1997|08|06}}\n| summary = [[Controlled flight into terrain]] due to [[pilot error]], insufficient training and [[Pilot fatigue|fatigue]]\n| site = [[Nimitz Hill]], [[Asan, Guam|Asan]], [[Guam]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|13|27|19|N|144|43|58|E|region:GU_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Boeing 747|Boeing 747-3B5]]\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[Korean Air]]\n| tail_number = [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19970806-0 HL7468]\n| origin = [[Gimpo International Airport|Kimpo International Airport]]\n| stopover = \n| stopover0 = \n| last_stopover = \n| destination = [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]]\n| passengers = 237\n| crew = 17\n| fatalities = 229{{efn|name=\"fatality footnote\"|This figure includes a 229th fatality that occurred on October 10th, more than 30 days after the accident. The NTSB however classifies them as a survivor with \"serious\" injuries in accordance with regulations.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|1}}}}\n| injuries = 25\n| missing = \n| survivors = 25 (Initially 26)\n| IATA = KE801\n| ICAO = KAL801\n| callsign = KOREAN AIR 801\n| occupants = 254\n}}\n'''Korean Air Flight 801''' (KE801, KAL801) was a scheduled international passenger flight operated by [[Korean Air]]. The flight crashed on August 6, 1997, on approach to [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]], in the [[United States]] territory of [[Guam]], killing 229{{efn|name=\"fatality footnote\"}} of the 254 people aboard. The aircraft crashed on [[Nimitz Hill]] in [[Asan, Guam|Asan]], [[Guam]], while on approach to the airport.<ref name=\"GuamHome\">{{Cite web|url=http://ns.gov.gu/guam/indexmain.html|title=Korean Air Flt 801 - Official Guam Crash Site Information Web Center|website=ns.gov.gu|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref> The [[NTSB|National Transportation Safety Board]] cites poor communication between the flight crew as probable cause for the crash, along with the captain\u2019s poor decision making on the [[Instrument approach|non-precision approach]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Reports/AAR0001.pdf|title=Controlled Flight Into Terrain Korean Air Flight 801 Boeing 747-300, HL7468 Nimitz Hill, Guam August 6, 1997|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2000|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board|location=Washington D.C.|id=NTSB/AAR-00/01|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Aircraft and crew ==\n\n=== Aircraft ===\n[[File:Boeing 747-3B5, Korean Air AN0610287.jpg|thumb|right|The aircraft involved in the accident, HL7468, taxiing at Paris Charles de Gaulle Airport in 1985]]\nFlight 801 was normally flown by an [[Airbus A300]]; since [[Korean Air]] had scheduled the August 5\u20136 flight to transport Chamorro athletes to the [[Pacific Games|South Pacific Mini Games]] in [[American Samoa]],<ref name=\"Transcripts\">\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/transcripts.html Transcripts Between Guam Airport Tower and KA801 before Crash].\" ''Government of [[Guam]]''. Retrieved on August 30, 2010.</ref> the airline designated HL7468, a 12-year-old [[Boeing 747|Boeing 747-300]] delivered to Korean Air on December 12, 1984,<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|16,28}} to fly the route that night.<ref name=\"Transcripts\" /><ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/indexmain.html Official Guam Crash Site Center \u2013 Korean Air Flt 801],\" ''Government of Guam''</ref>\n\n=== Crew ===\nThe flight was under the command of 42-year-old Captain Park Yong-chul ([[Hangul|Korean]]: \ubc15\uc6a9\ucca0, [[Hanja]]: \u6734\u93de\u5586, [[Revised Romanization of Korean|RR]]: ''Bak Yong-cheol''. [[McCune-Reischauer|M-R]]: ''Pak Yongch'\u014fl'')<ref>\"[http://starbulletin.com/98/03/25/news/story1.html Two Systems Down in KAL 801 Crash],\" ''[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]''</ref> The captain had close to 9,000 hours of flight time (3,192 of them on the Boeing 747) and had recently received a Flight Safety Award for negotiating a 747 engine failure at low altitude.<ref name=\"Mayday Final Approach\" /> Park had originally been scheduled to fly to [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]; since he did not have enough rest for the Dubai trip, he was reassigned to Flight 801.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|3,15}}  The first officer was 40-year-old Song Kyung-ho ([[Hangul|Korean]]: \uc1a1\uacbd\ud638, [[Hanja]]: \u5b8b\u6176\u660a, RR: ''Song Gyeong-ho'', M-R: ''Song Ky\u014fngho''), who had more than 4,000 hours' flying experience (including 1,560 hours on the Boeing 747), and the flight engineer was 57-year-old Nam Suk-hoon ([[Hangul|Korean]]: \ub0a8\uc11d\ud6c8, [[Hanja]]: \u5357\u932b\u85b0, RR: ''Nam Seok-hun'', M-R: ''Nam S\u014fkhun''),<ref>\"[https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/542233.pdf DOCKET NO.: SA-517 EXHIBIT NO. 2F].\" ''ntsb.gov'' [[National Transportation Safety Board]]</ref> a veteran pilot with more than 13,000 flight hours, including 1,573 hours on the Boeing 747.\n\n==Accident==\n[[File:Guam2.ogv|thumb|NTSB animation of Flight 801's descent]]\n[[File:KAL801QT3.ogv|thumb|NTSB animation of Flight 801's descent, showing the aircraft's distance from the runway]] \n[[File:Korean Air Flight 801 crash, Guam air traffic control recording (August 1997).oga|thumb|ATC traffic after KAL 801 failed to land at the airport]]{{Expand section|date=November 2019}}\nFlight 801 departed from Seoul-Kimpo International Airport (now [[Gimpo Airport|Gimpo International Airport]]) at 8:53&nbsp;p.m. (9:53&nbsp;p.m. Guam time) on August 5 on its way to Guam. It carried three flight crew members (the two pilots and the flight engineer), 14 flight attendants, and 237 passengers from 4 countries,<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|11,23}} a total of 254 people. Of the passengers, three were children between the ages of 2 and 12 and three were 24 months old or younger.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|45,57}} Six of the passengers were Korean Air flight attendants, who were [[deadheading (employee)|deadheading]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|3,15}}\n\nThe flight experienced some turbulence but was uneventful until shortly after 1:00&nbsp;a.m. on August 6, as the jet was preparing to land. There was heavy rain at Guam so visibility was significantly reduced and the crew attempted an instrument landing. The [[glideslope]] Instrument Landing System (ILS) for runway 6L was out of service; Captain Park believed it was in service, however, and at 1:35 am managed to pick up a signal that was later identified to be from an irrelevant electronic device on the ground.  The crew noticed that the aircraft was descending very steeply, and noted several times that the airport \"is not in sight.\" Despite protests from flight engineer Nam that the detected signal was not the glide-slope indicator, Park pressed on. The crew lowered the landing gear and continued to prepare the aircraft for landing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/09/us/in-asiana-crash-investigation-early-focus-is-on-the-crews-actions.html|title=In Asiana Crash Investigation, Early Focus Is on the Crew\u2019s Actions|last=Wald|first=Matthew L.|date=2013-07-08|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-07-22|last2=Onishi|first2=Norimitsu|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> 12 seconds before impact, the Ground Proximity Warning system activated, warning the crew about their actual altitude. First officer Song declared a missed approach, and captain Park declared a go-around, but it was too late. At 1:42 am, the aircraft's main landing gear struck a fuel pipeline, and crashed into Nimitz Hill near Asan, Guam. The crash site was about {{convert|3|nmi|mi km}} short of the runway, at an altitude of {{convert|660|ft}}.\n\nOf the 254 people on board, 229 died as a result of the crash. One survivor, 36-year-old Hyun Seong Hong<!--Hong is an American, so put in Western order--> (\ud64d\ud604\uc131, also spelled ''Hong Hyun Sung'') of the United States, occupied Seat 3B in first class, and said that the crash occurred so quickly that the passengers \"had no time to scream\"<ref name=\"PilotErrorNYT\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/08/world/pilot-error-is-suspected-in-crash-on-guam.html|title=Pilot Error Is Suspected in Crash on Guam|last=Pollack|first=Andrew|date=1997-08-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and likened the crash to \"a scene from a film.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|45}}<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19970808/ai_n14123263 Anger and tears as Guam crash families beg to see dead] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216075715/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19970808/ai_n14123263 |date=December 16, 2008 }}, ''[[The Independent]]''</ref>\n\n== Rescue ==\n[[Image:Korean Air Flight 801 wreckage.jpg|thumb|Wreckage of HL7468 burns at the Sasa Valley crash site.]]\nThe rescue effort was hampered by the weather, terrain, and other problems. Emergency vehicles could not approach due to the fuel pipeline destroyed by the crash and blocking the narrow road. [[United States Navy]] Seabees of NMCB133 were some of the first on the scene as they utilized their earth moving equipment to clear roadways and timber from the crash site approach. The Seabees used backhoes to crack open the still-burning plane to rescue survivors and erected mortuary tents for first responders. There was confusion over the administration of the effort; the crash occurred on land owned by the [[United States Navy]] but civil authorities initially claimed authority. The hull had disintegrated, and [[jet fuel]] in the wing tanks had sparked a fire that was still burning eight hours after impact.\n\n===Rika Matsuda===\n\nGovernor [[Carl T.C. Gutierrez]] found 11-year-old Rika Matsuda, from [[Japan]], who boarded the flight with her mother, 44-year-old Shigeko.<ref name=\"Honeymoon\">\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/honeymoon-flight-that-ended-in-horror-1244140.html Honeymoon flight that ended in horror].\" ''[[The Independent]]''. Thursday August 7, 1997. Retrieved on August 30, 2010.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-61001878 Jet hell Rika's scars will last forever.],\" ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]''</ref> They were heading to Guam on vacation. Rika Matsuda described what happened to her and her mother to interpreters.<ref name=\"PilotErrorNYT\"/> Shigeko could not free herself from the aircraft and told Rika to run away. Luggage piled on the girl and her mother as the crash occurred; Rika Matsuda said her mother, unable to free herself, asked her to leave.<ref name=\"PilotErrorNYT\"/> Shigeko died in the fire. After escaping from the aircraft, Rika discovered a surviving [[flight attendant]], Lee Yong Ho (\uc774\uc6a9\ud638). They stayed together until Gutierrez discovered them.<ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/miracle/ Korean Air Survivor \u2013 Rika's Miracle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126062957/http://ns.gov.gu/guam/miracle/ |date=2007-11-26 }},\" ''Government of Guam''</ref> Rika Matsuda, treated at Guam Memorial Hospital in [[Tamuning, Guam|Tamuning]], was released on August 7, 1997, and was reunited with her father, Tatsuo Matsuda. The two were then escorted to the Governor House where they were the guests of Gutierrez and the [[First Lady of Guam]], Geri Gutierrez, for several days; afterwards Rika and Tatsuo Matsuda flew to Japan.<ref name=\"GuamHome\"/><ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/miracle/ Korean Air Survivor \u2013 Rika's Miracle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126062957/http://ns.gov.gu/guam/miracle/ |date=2007-11-26 }}.\" ''Government of Guam''. Retrieved on February 13, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Investigation and probable cause==\n\nA special weather observation made at 01:32 ten minutes before the impact reported:\n\n<blockquote>Wind 090\u00b0 at 6 knots; visibility\u20147 miles; present weather\u2014shower vicinity; sky condition\u2014scattered 1,600 feet, broken 2,500 feet, overcast 5,000 feet [above ground level]; temperature\u201427\u00b0 C; dew point\u201425\u00b0 C; altimeter setting 29.85 inches Hg; remarks\u2014showers vicinity northwest-northeast.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|20}} </blockquote>\n\nAnother special weather observation made at 01:47 five minutes after the impact reported:\n\n<blockquote>Wind variable at 4 knots; visibility\u20145 miles; present weather\u2014light rain shower; sky condition\u2014few 1,500 feet, scattered 2,500 feet, overcast 4,000 feet; temperature 26\u00b0 C; dew point 24\u00b0 C; altimeter 29.85 inches Hg.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|21}} </blockquote>\n\nThe U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) investigation report stated that a contributing factor was that the ATC [[Minimum Safe Altitude Warning]] (MSAW) system at Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport had been deliberately modified so as to limit spurious alarms and could not detect an approaching aircraft that was below minimum safe altitude.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|175}} The probable cause of the accident was the captain's poor execution of the [[Instrument approach|non-precision approach]],<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|175}} the captain's fatigue, poor communication between the flight crew, and Korean Air's lack of flight crew training.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|175}} The crew had been using an outdated flight map that was missing a 724 foot obstruction symbol depicted at the NIMITZ VOR and that map stated the Minimum Safe Altitude while crossing the NIMITZ VOR for a landing aircraft was {{convert|1300|ft}} as opposed to the updated altitude of {{convert|1440|ft}}.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|36}} Flight 801 crashed near the NIMITZ VOR, which is situated on Nimitz Hill at a height of {{convert|680|ft}} at 1:42 am, when it descended below the minimum safe altitude of {{convert|1440|ft}} during its landing approach. The report also identified that the captain may have mistakenly believed that the airplane was closer to the airport\nthan it was and that there may have been confusion about the location of the [[Distance Measuring Equipment]] (DME) in relation to the airport, with the crew anticipating the VOR/DME to be located at the airport. The DME was sited at the NIMITZ VOR some {{Convert|3.3|nmi|mi km|abbr=on}} from the airport and such a configuration had not been part of Korean Air's simulator training, the crew's training for such non-precision approaches having been carried out in scenarios where the DME was located at the airport. Nevertheless the correct DME distances were shown on the approach chart.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|144}}\n\nThe NTSB presented its findings on March 24, 25 and 26, 1998 in the [[Hawaii Convention Center]] in [[Honolulu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/67326.pdf|title=Public Hearing in Connection with the Investigation of Aircraft Accident Korean Air Flight 801, B-747-300 Agana, Guam August 6, 1997 - Transcript 1|date=March 24, 1998|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board}}</ref><ref name=\"pubhearing\">{{cite web|url=https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/67328.pdf|title=Public Hearing in Connection with the Investigation of Aircraft Accident Korean Air Flight 801, B-747-300 Agana, Guam August 6, 1997 - Transcript 2|date=March 25, 1998|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108060020/http://www.ntsb.gov/events/kal801/trans_980325.htm|archivedate=January 8, 2007|url-status=}}</ref><ref name=\"pubhearingg\">{{cite web|url=https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/67210.pdf|title=Public Hearing in Connection with the Investigation of Aircraft Accident Korean Air Flight 801, B-747-300 Agana, Guam August 6, 1997 - Transcript 3|date=March 26, 1998|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070109090647/http://www.ntsb.gov/events/kal801/trans_980326.htm|archivedate=January 9, 2007|url-status=}}</ref>\n\nThe section of the report entitled \"Probable Cause\" concluded:\n\n<blockquote>The National Transportation Safety Board determines that the probable cause of this accident was the captain\u2019s failure to adequately brief and execute the non-precision approach and the first officer\u2019s and flight engineer\u2019s failure to effectively monitor and cross-check the captain\u2019s execution of the approach.  Contributing to these failures were the captain\u2019s fatigue and Korean Air\u2019s inadequate flight crew training.\n\nContributing to the accident was the Federal Aviation Administration\u2019s intentional inhibition of the [[MSAW|minimum safe altitude warning system]] at Guam and the agency\u2019s failure to adequately manage the system.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|xi,175}}</blockquote>\n\n==Passengers==\n[[File:KoreanAir801Survivorloc.JPG|thumb|Locations of the survivors ([[:File:KoreanAir801Survivorloc EN.svg|Greyscale version for colorblind persons]])]]\n\n===Deaths and injuries===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" \n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n!rowspan=2|Nationality||colspan=2|Passengers||colspan=2|Crew||colspan=2|Total\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n!Total||Killed||Total||Killed||Total||Killed\n|- valign=top\n|South Korea||style=\"text-align:center;\" |218||style=\"text-align:center;\" |201|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |17||style=\"text-align:center;\" |14||style=\"text-align:center;\" |235||style=\"text-align:center;\" |215\n|- valign=top\n|New Zealand||style=\"text-align:center;\" |1||style=\"text-align:center;\" |0||{{n/a|-}}||{{n/a|-}}||style=\"text-align:center;\" |1||style=\"text-align:center;\" |0\n|- valign=top\n|United States||style=\"text-align:center;\" |13||style=\"text-align:center;\" |10||{{n/a|-}}||{{n/a|-}}||style=\"text-align:center;\" |13||style=\"text-align:center;\" |10\n|- valign=top\n|Japan||style=\"text-align:center;\" |5||style=\"text-align:center;\" |4||{{n/a|-}}||{{n/a|-}}||style=\"text-align:center;\" |5||style=\"text-align:center;\" |4\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|'''Total'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''237'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''215'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''17'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''14'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''254'''|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''229'''\n|}\n\nOf the 254 people on board, 223 \u2013 209 passengers and 14 crew members (all 3 flight crew and 11 cabin crew) \u2013 were killed at the crash site.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|45,57}}\n\nOf the 31 occupants found alive by rescue crews, two died en route to the hospital and a further three in hospital.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|3,15,45,57}} Among the survivors, 16 received burn injuries. The 26 survivors were initially treated at [[Guam Memorial Hospital]] (GMH) in [[Tamuning, Guam|Tamuning]] or at the U.S. Naval Hospital in [[Agana Heights, Guam|Agana Heights]]. Four were subsequently transferred to the U.S. Army Burn Center in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], [[Texas]].<ref name=\"GuamHome\"/><ref>\"[http://www.burncarerehab.com/pt/re/jburncr/abstract.01253092-200609000-00014.htm;jsessionid=LFjQcWfxBHX8YNpbJy95J2vMdcLZfTgyjpvz0bJbf6Jdxf35XTxz!-1004083789!181195629!8091!-1 Airplane Crash in Guam, August 6, 1997: The Aeromedical Evacuation Response].\"</ref> and eight to University Hospital in Seoul. On October 10 the same year, one passengers died of their injuries, bringing the amount of fatalities to 229 and the amount of survivors to 25.<ref>\"[http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=41097 One Crash Victim Dies, Three Cling to Life at Burn Center].\" ''U.S. Department of Defense''.</ref><ref>Wiechmann, Lori. \"[http://www.onlineathens.com/1997/081297/0812.korean.html Last member of Atlanta family on downed Korean jet dies]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\" ''[[Athens Daily News]]''. August 12, 1997. Retrieved on July 1, 2011.</ref><ref>\"[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970902&slug=2558056 Daily Briefing].\" ''[[The Seattle Times]]''. Tuesday September 2, 1997. Corrected on September 8, 1997. \"Two more people who initially survived last month's crash of a Korean Air jumbo jet in Guam have died, bringing the death toll to 228, a South Korean foreign ministry spokesman said today. Korean flight attendant Han Kyu-hee died on Saturday at Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio, Texas. Another South Korean, Jung Young-hak, a passenger, died on Sunday in the same facility.\"</ref><ref>Gillert, Douglas J. \"[http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=41097 One Crash Victim Dies, Three Cling to Life at Burn Center].\" [[U.S. Department of Defense]]. Retrieved on June 30, 2011. \"The other victims brought here were Se Jin Ju, 28; Kyu Hee Han, 29; and Young Hak Jung, 39, all South Korean citizens. Along with Chung, they were the most severely burned survivors and needed the kind of treatment the Brooke Army Medical Center burn unit here provides.\"</ref><ref>\"[https://www.ntsb.gov/safety/safety-recs/recletters/A00_19_20.pdf Safety Recommendation Date:  January 27, 2000 In reply refer to:  A-00-19 and  -20].\" [[National Transportation Safety Board]]. Retrieved on June 30, 2011. \" A passenger with serious injuries died at the U.S. Army Medical Center in San Antonio, Texas, on October 10, 1997, but is not officially listed as a fatality because the passenger\u2019s death occurred more than 30 days after the accident\"</ref>\n\nThere were 22 passengers and three flight attendants who survived the crash with serious injuries.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|11,23,45,57}}<!-- This includes the person who died in October -->\n\n===Notable passengers===\n[[Shin Ki-ha]], a four-term South Korean parliamentarian and former leader of the [[National Congress for New Politics]], traveled with his wife and around 20 party members. Shin and his wife were killed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/05/guam.late/ |title=Guam |accessdate=March 6, 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050306010328/http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9708/05/guam.late/ |archivedate=March 6, 2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage-9801E1DC173CF934A3575BC0A961958260.html|title=For Relatives Of Victims, Anger Adds To Anguish|last=Gargan|first=Edward A.|date=August 7, 1997|website=|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Identification and repatriation of bodies===\n\nOn August 13, 1997, 12 sets of remains were brought to Guam's airport to be readied to be flown back to Seoul. Clifford Guzman, a governor's aide, said that two of the 12 were taken back to the morgue. Of the 10, one was misidentified and had to be switched before takeoff. The 10 bodies transported to Seoul were of seven passengers and three female flight attendants. On the same date, an NTSB family affairs official named Matthew Furman said that in total, by that date, 46 bodies had been identified.<ref name=\"Seattletimes\">\"[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970813&slug=2554557 Guam Crash Aftermath Upsets Kin].\" ''[[The Seattle Times]]''. August 13, 1997.</ref>\n\n==After the crash==\n[[File:KALMemorialAsanGuam.jpg|thumb|Korean Air Flight 801 Memorial in [[Asan, Guam]]]]\nAfter the crash occurred, the airline provided several flights for around 300 relatives so that they could go to the crash site.<ref>Coleman, Joe. \"[http://archives.savannahnow.com/sav_pdf_archive/text/fr852/A_2474131.pdf Survivors recount the fiery last moments] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324173658/http://archives.savannahnow.com/sav_pdf_archive/text/fr852/A_2474131.pdf |date=2012-03-24 }}.\" ''[[The Associated Press]]'' at the ''[[Savannah Morning News]]''. Thursday August 7, 1997. 10A. Retrieved on July 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn August 13, 1997, 50 protesters staged a sit-in at Guam Airport, saying that the recovery of the dead was taking too long; they sat on blankets and sheets of paper at the Korean Air counter.<ref name=\"Seattletimes\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nOn August 5, 1998, the first anniversary of the crash, a black [[marble]] [[obelisk]] was unveiled on the crash site as a memorial to the victims.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nAfter the accident, Korean Air services to Guam were suspended for more than four years, leading to reduced tourist spending in Guam and reduced revenues for Korean Air.<ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/specifics.html Specifics of Crash Site Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216081618/http://ns.gov.gu/guam/specifics.html |date=2008-12-16 }}.\" ''Guam Government''. Retrieved on December 9, 2008.</ref> When Seoul-Guam services resumed in December 2001,<ref>\"[http://archives.starbulletin.com/2001/12/28/business/story3.html Korean Air resumes service to Guam for the first time in 4 years].\" ''[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]''. Friday December 28, 2001. Retrieved on April 29, 2009.</ref> the flight number was changed to 805. The flight number for its Seoul-Guam route is now 111 and operates out of [[Incheon Airport|Incheon]] instead of Gimpo, using a [[Boeing 777-300]] or an [[Airbus A330]].\n\nIn 2000, a lawsuit was settled in the amount of $70,000,000 [[United States dollar]]s on behalf of 54 families against the airline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speiserkrause.com/cases/|title=Our Work and Past Cases|website=speiserkrause.com|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNew Zealander Barry Small, a helicopter pilot and a survivor of the accident, lobbied for safer storage of duty-free alcohol and redesigns of crossbars on airline seats; he said that the storage of duty-free alcohol on Flight 801 contributed to spreading of the fire and the crossbars injured passengers to the point where they could not escape from the aircraft (Small himself was injured when he broke his leg on one of the crossbars during the crash, but was still able to escape the aircraft).<ref name=\"Mayday Final Approach\" /><ref>\"[https://dms.ntsb.gov/public/9000-9499/9289/67313.pdf Exhibit 16C \u2013 Korean Air Flight 801].\" [[National Transportation Safety Board]]. Retrieved on June 26, 2009.</ref><!--The NTSB recorded Barry Small's testimony about the alcohol-->\n\nThe Government of Guam moved its website about the Korean Air crash after the Spamcop program alerted the government that [[advance fee fraud]] spam from Nigeria used the website link as a part of the scam.<ref>\"[http://ns.gov.gu/guam/ This webpage has been cancelled.]\"{{sic}} <!--Please do not correct to \"canceled\"-->''Government of Guam''. Retrieved on April 29, 2009.</ref> Scam e-mails used names of passengers, such as Sean Burke, as part of the fraud.<ref>Larson, Aaron. \"[https://www.expertlaw.com/library/consumer/spam_email_fraud3.html False Promises of Inheritance \u2013 Spam Email Fraud].\" ''Law Offices of Aaron Larson'' at ExpertLaw. July 2004. Retrieved on May 13, 2009.</ref>\n\nFollowing the Korean Air 801 crash, it was brought to the [[NTSB]]'s attention that foreign carriers flying in and out of the US were not covered by the Aviation Disaster Family Assistance Act of 1996 and Korean Air did not have a plan to deal with the situation they encountered. As a result, [[US Congress]] passed the Foreign Air Carrier Family Support Act of 1997 to require those carriers to file family assistance plans and fulfill the same family support requirements as domestic airlines. Not only does the Act ensure that all victims and family members will be treated equitably, regardless of the carrier they use, it also impels many carriers that may not have thought about family assistance issues to give them due consideration in their emergency response plans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/news/speeches/JimHall/Pages/Remarks_before_the_International_Symposium_on_Family_Victim_Assistance_for_Transportation_Disasters_Arlington_Virginia.aspx|title=Remarks before the International Symposium on Family & Victim Assistance for Transportation Disasters, Arlington, Virginia|date=September 28, 1998|website=ntsb.gov|publisher=National Transportation Safety Board|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*[[Malcolm Gladwell]] discusses the crash in the context of cultural effects on power structures in his book ''[[Outliers (book)|Outliers]]''.<ref>Outliers ch 7, The Ethnic Theory of Plane Crashes, pp 209\u2013223</ref>\n*The [[Discovery Channel Canada]] / [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] TV series ''[[Mayday (Canadian TV series)|Mayday]]'' (also called ''Air Crash Investigation'' or ''Air Emergency'') dramatized the accident in a 2007 episode titled ''Final Approach'', although it was also titled ''Missed Approach'' for the episode on ''Air Disasters''.,<ref name=\"Mayday Final Approach\">{{Cite episode|title=Final Approach|series=[[Mayday (Canadian TV series)|Mayday]]|network=[[Discovery Channel Canada]] / [[National Geographic Channel]]|season=4|year=2007|episode-link=|series-link=|date=|number=|url=http://www.discoverycivilization.ca/shows/episodedetails.aspx?eid=581&sid=568|access-date=June 26, 2009}}{{dead link|date=December 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> and \"Blind Landing\" for the UK.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|South Korea|United States|Aviation|1990s}}\n* [[Impact of culture on aviation safety]]\n* [[Avianca Flight 011]]\n* [[American Airlines Flight 965]]\n* [[Air Inter Flight 148]]\n* [[Air New Zealand Flight 901]]\n* [[Asiana Airlines Flight 733]]\n* [[Crew resource management]]\n* [[Ground proximity warning system]] (GPWS)\n* [[List of accidents and incidents involving commercial aircraft]]\n* [[Prinair Flight 277]]\n* [[Colgan Air Flight 3407]]\n* [[List of aviation accidents and incidents involving CFIT]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n*[[National Transportation Safety Board]] [http://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Reports/AAR0001.pdf Korean Air Flight 801 Final Accident Report]\n\n'''Further reading'''\n*[[Politics of Guam|Government of Guam]]: [http://ns.gov.gu/guam/indexmain.html Guam Crash Site Center \u2013 Korean Air Flight 801], photographs, passenger manifest, scanned news articles, and related links\n* [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] ''[[Newshour with Jim Lehrer]]'': \"[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/transportation/july-dec97/koreanair_8-6.html Tragedy on Guam],\" August 6, 1997\n* \"[http