ippi}}|| Tiffany Andrade<br>{{flag|New Jersey}} || Lindsey Jo Harrington<br>{{flag|Oklahoma}}|| LauRen Merola<br>{{flag|Pennsylvania}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2009|2009]] || [[Kristen Dalton (Miss USA)|Kristen Dalton]]<br>{{flag|North Carolina}}|| [[Carrie Prejean]]<br>{{flag|California}}|| Alicia-Monique Blanco<br>{{flag|Arizona}} || Laura Chukanov<br>{{flag|Utah|1913}}|| Maria Elizabeth Montgomery<br>{{flag|Kentucky}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2010|2010]] || [[Rima Fakih]]<br>{{flag|Michigan}}|| Morgan Woolard<br>{{flag|Oklahoma}}|| Samantha Casey<br>{{flag|Virginia}} || [[Jessica Hartman]]<br>{{flag|Colorado}}|| Katie Whittier<br>{{flag|Maine}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2011|2011]] || [[Alyssa Campanella]]<br>{{flag|California}}||[[Ashley Durham]]<br>{{flag|Tennessee}}|| [[Madeline Mitchell]]<br>{{flag|Alabama}} || [[Ana Rodriguez (Miss Texas USA)|Ana Rodriguez]]<br>{{flag|Texas}} || colspan=2 rowspan=1 {{n/a|Not awarded}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2012|2012]] || [[Olivia Culpo]]<br>{{flag|Rhode Island}}<br>(Miss Universe 2012)|| [[Nana Meriwether]]<br>{{flag|Maryland}}<br>(Assumed Miss USA 2012 Title)|| [[Audrey Bolte]]<br>{{flag|Ohio}} || Jade Kelsall<br>{{flag|Nevada}}|| Jazz Wilkins<br>{{flag|Georgia (U.S. state)|name=Georgia}} || colspan=1 rowspan=1 {{n/a|Not awarded}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2013|2013]] || [[Erin Brady]]<br>{{flag|Connecticut}}|| Mary-Margaret McCord<br>{{flag|Alabama}}|| Stacie Juris<br>{{flag|Illinois}} || Marissa Powell<br>{{flag|Utah}}|| Ali Nugent<br>{{flag|Texas}} || Megan Pinckney<br>{{flag|South Carolina}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2014|2014]] || [[Nia Sanchez]]<br>{{flag|Nevada}}||[[Audra Mari]]<br>{{flag|North Dakota}}|| Tiana Griggs<br>{{flag|Georgia (U.S. state)|name=Georgia}} || Brittany Guidry<br>{{flag|Louisiana}}|| Brittany Oldehoff<br>{{flag|Florida}} || Carlyn Bradarich<br>{{flag|Iowa}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2015|2015]] || [[Olivia Jordan]]<br>{{flag|Oklahoma}}|| Ylianna Guerra<br>{{flag|Texas}}|| [[Anea Garcia]]<br>{{flag|Rhode Island}} || Brittany McGowan<br>{{flag|Nevada}}|| [[Mam\u00e9 Adjei]]<br>{{flag|Maryland}} || colspan=1 rowspan=1 {{n/a|Not awarded}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2016|2016]] || [[Deshauna Barber]]<br>{{flag|District of Columbia}}||[[Chelsea Hardin]]<br>{{flag|Hawaii}}|| Emanii Davis<br>{{flag|Georgia (U.S. state)|name=Georgia}} || colspan=3 rowspan=4 {{n/a|Not awarded}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2017|2017]] || [[K\u00e1ra McCullough]]<br>{{flag|District of Columbia}}|| Chhavi Verg<br>{{flag|New Jersey}}|| [[Meridith Gould]]<br>{{flag|Minnesota}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2018|2018]] || [[Sarah Rose Summers]]<br>{{flag|Nebraska}}||[[Caelynn Miller-Keyes]]<br>{{flag|North Carolina}}|| Carolina Urrea<br>{{flag|Nevada}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Miss USA 2019|2019]] || [[Cheslie Kryst]]<br>{{flag|North Carolina}}|| Alejandra Gonz\u00e1lez<br>{{flag|New Mexico}}|| Triana Browne<br>{{flag|Oklahoma}}\n|-\n| [[Miss USA 2020|2020]] || colspan=\"6\" {{tba|To be announced}}\n|}\n\n==Awards==\nThe awards most frequently presented at Miss USA are Miss Amity (also known as Miss Congeniality) and Miss Photogenic.\n\nThe Miss Amity Award is chosen by the delegates, and recognizes those who are the friendliest and make the pageant experience the most enjoyable. From 1952 to 1964, when the Miss USA and Miss Universe pageants were concurrent events, the award could be won by a contestant competing either for Miss USA or Miss Universe. In fact, in 1960, there was a tie, with the award going to [[Miss Universe Myanmar|Miss Universe Burma]], Myint Myint May, and [[Miss Louisiana USA]], Rebecca Fletcher. In 2015, [[Miss Alaska USA|Alaska]] and [[Miss Delaware USA|Delaware]] tied for the Miss Congeniality award. [[Miss Vermont USA|Vermont]] and [[Miss Wyoming USA|Wyoming]] have won five Miss Amity/Congeniality awards, two more than any other state.\n\nThe Miss Photogenic prize was first awarded in 1965 and was chosen by journalists until 1996 when it was chosen by an internet vote for the first time. There has been only one tie in this award's history: in 1980, when it was shared between [[Jineane Ford]] of [[Miss Arizona USA|Arizona]] and Elizabeth Kim Thomas of [[Miss Ohio USA|Ohio]]. The state that has won the most Photogenic awards is [[Miss Virginia USA|Virginia]].\n\n[[Miss Louisiana USA|Louisiana]] won both the first Miss Amity and Photogenic awards given to a Miss USA contestant.\n\nOther awards that have been presented include Best State Costume (1962\u20131993), Style (1995\u20132001) and Most Beautiful Eyes (1993). In 1998, a special Distinguished Achievement award was given to [[Halle Berry]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Shawnae Jebbia of Massachusetts Crowned \"Miss USA 1998\" |publisher=Business Wire|date=2007-03-11}}</ref> Berry was [[Miss Ohio USA]] 1986 and placed 1st runner-up to [[Christy Fichtner]] of [[Miss Texas USA|Texas]]. She later went on to become an acclaimed actress and [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] winner.\n\n==Locations==\nIn the first eight years of competition (1952\u20131959), the Miss USA pageant was held in [[Long Beach, California]]. The competition moved to [[Miami Beach, Florida]] in 1960 and stayed there until 1971. In 1972, the pageant was held in [[Puerto Rico]], the only time the pageant has been held outside the continental United States. That pageant was rocked by an explosion at the host hotel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Explosion of undetermined cause rocks site of Miss USA pageant|publisher=New York Times Abstracts|date=1972-05-21|page=35}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1972 onwards, the pageant has been held in various locations, generally being held in each location for two to three years.\n\nAs of 2019, the pageant has been held in the following states:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n*'''[[Alabama]]'''\n**[[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] (1989)\n*'''[[California]]'''\n**[[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] (1952\u20131959)\n**[[Los Angeles]] (2004, 2007) \n*'''[[Florida]]'''\n**[[Miami Beach, Florida|Miami Beach]] (1960\u20131971)\n**[[Lakeland, Florida|Lakeland]] (1984\u20131985)\n**[[Miami]] (1986)\n*'''[[Indiana]]'''\n**[[Gary, Indiana|Gary]] (2001\u20132002)\n*'''[[Kansas]]'''\n**[[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] (1990\u20131993)\n{{col-3}}\n*'''[[Louisiana]]'''\n**[[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] (1997\u20131998, 2018)\n**[[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] (2014\u20132015)\n*'''[[Maryland]]'''\n**[[Baltimore]] (2005\u20132006)\n*'''[[Missouri]]'''\n**[[Branson, Missouri|Branson]] (1999\u20132000)\n*'''[[Mississippi]]'''\n**[[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]] (1979\u20131982)\n*'''[[Nevada]]'''\n**[[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] (2008\u20132013, 2016\u20132017)\n**[[Reno, Nevada|Reno]] (2019)\n{{col-3}}\n*'''[[New Mexico]]'''\n**[[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]] (1987)\n*'''[[New York (state)|New York]]'''\n**[[New York City]] (1973)\n**[[Niagara Falls, New York|Niagara Falls]] (1974\u20131976)\n*'''[[South Carolina]]'''\n**[[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] (1977\u20131978)\n*'''[[Tennessee]]'''\n**[[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] (1983)\n*'''[[Texas]]'''\n**[[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]] (1988)\n**[[South Padre Island, Texas|South Padre Island]] (1994\u20131996)\n**[[San Antonio]] (2003)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Special feature episodes==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2019}}\nSince 2003, a number of delegates have been involved in special episodes of regular programs broadcast by [[NBC]]. From 2003\u20132005, six delegates each year were chosen to participate in a special Miss USA edition of ''[[Fear Factor]]'', with the victorious contestant taking the title \"Miss Fear Factor USA\" and a prize of [[United States dollar|$]]50,000 ($25,000 of which was to be donated to a charity of the winner's choice). These were broadcast immediately prior to the live pageant broadcast.\n\nIn 2006, [[Chelsea Cooley]] and twenty-six delegates participated as briefcase models in a Miss USA special of ''[[Deal or No Deal (U.S. game show)|Deal or No Deal]]''.\n\nIn 2010, ten Miss USA and Miss Universe winners competed for charity on a special \"Last Beauty Standing\" edition of ''[[Minute to Win It]]''.\n\n==Reality television==\nMany Miss USA and Miss Teen USA delegates have participated in [[reality television]] shows and other television [[game show]]s. Well known delegates who later competed in reality shows are [[Danni Boatwright]], winner of ''[[Survivor: Guatemala]]'' and contestant of ''[[Survivor: Winners at War]]'', [[Christie Lee Woods]] of ''[[The Amazing Race 5]]'' and ''[[The Amazing Race 31]]'' and [[Nicole O'Brian]] also of ''The Amazing Race 5'', [[Shandi Finnessey]] and [[Shanna Moakler]] on ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', [[Jennifer Murphy]] of ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 4)|The Apprentice 4]]'', [[Tori Fiorenza]] of ''[[The Challenge: Cutthroat]]'', [[Hannah Brown]] of ''[[The Bachelor (season 23)|The Bachelor]]'' and ''[[The Bachelorette (season 15)|The Bachelorette]]'' and [[Caelynn Miller-Keyes]], [[Alayah Benavidez]], [[Kelsey Weier]] and [[Victoria Paul]] also of ''The Bachelor''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poptower.com/tori-hall-fiorenza-real-world.htm |title=Tori Hall Fiorenza Real World Challenge pictures, bio, dating |publisher=Poptower.com |date=1986-12-20 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, ''Pageant Place'', a reality television show featuring [[Rachel Smith]], [[Riyo Mori]], [[Hilary Cruz]], [[Katie Blair]], and [[Tara Conner]] aired on MTV.<ref>{{cite news|title=Three Crowns Sharing One Apartment|work=The New York Times|date=2007-10-10|first=Felicia|last=Lee}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 2011, [[Bravo (U.S. TV network)|Bravo]] Television's [[Andy Cohen (television personality)|Andy Cohen]] co-hosted the event's 60th anniversary live in Las Vegas with ''[[E! News]]'' and ''[[Fashion Police]]'''s [[Giuliana Rancic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Andy-Cohen-Miss-USA-1034314.aspx |title=Andy Cohen on Hosting the Miss USA Pageant: I Want to Bring Out the Competition - Today's News: Our Take |publisher=TVGuide.com |date=2011-06-17 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref> They also hosted the 2012 pageant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/06/04/olivia-culpo-crowned-miss-usa-2012-beats-latina-beauties/ |title=Miss USA 2012: Olivia Culpo Crowned, Beats Latina Beauties &#124; Fox News Latino |publisher=Latino.foxnews.com |date=2012-06-04 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Miss U.S. International]]\n* [[United States representatives at Miss World]]\n* [[Miss Earth United States]]\n* [[Miss Teen USA]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Miss USA}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.missusa.com/}}\n\n{{MUO}}\n{{Miss USA}}\n{{Miss USA state}}\n{{Miss Universe countries and territories}}\n{{FOXNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miss Usa}}\n[[Category:1952 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American awards]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageants in the United States|USA]]\n[[Category:CBS original programming]]\n[[Category:Miss Universe Organization]]\n[[Category:Miss USA| ]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1952]]\n[[Category:Miss Universe by country|USA]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Miss America|Miss World America|Miss U.S. International|Miss United States|Miss Earth United States}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox Organization\n|name         = Miss USA\n|image        = Miss USA Logo.png\n|image_border =\n|size         = 250\n|map          =\n|msize        =\n|mcaption     =\n|motto        =\n|formation    = {{Start date and age|1952|6|27}}\n|type         = [[Beauty pageant]]\n|headquarters = [[New York City]]\n|location     = {{USA}}\n|membership   = [[Miss Universe]]\n|language     = [[English language|English]]\n|leader_title = President\n|leader_name  = Paula Shugart\n|key_people   =\n|parent_organization = [[William Morris Endeavor|WME]]/[[IMG (company)|IMG]]\n|num_staff    =\n|budget       =\n|website      = {{URL|missusa.com}}\n}}\n'''Miss USA''' is an American [[beauty pageant]] that has been held annually since 1952 to select the entrant from United States in the [[Miss Universe]] pageant. The [[Miss Universe Organization]] operates both pageants, as well as [[Miss Teen USA]].\n\nThe pageant was owned by [[Donald Trump]] from 1996 to 2015 and was previously broadcast on [[NBC]]. In September 2015, [[William Morris Endeavor|WME]]/[[IMG (company)|IMG]] purchased the pageant from Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missuniverse.com/news/view/681#.VwS5E6QrKM-|title=WME-IMG ACQUIRES THE MISS UNIVERSE ORGANIZATION|date=September 14, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2016|work=[[Miss Universe]]}}</ref> Currently, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] holds the broadcast rights for the pageant.\n\nThe current Miss USA is [[Cheslie Kryst]] of [[Miss North Carolina USA|North Carolina]] who was crowned on May 2, 2019 at [[Grand Sierra Resort]] in [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]], [[Nevada]].\n\n==History==\nThe Miss USA pageant was conceived in 1950 when [[Yolande Betbeze]], winner of the [[Miss America]] pageant, refused to pose for publicity pictures while wearing a swimsuit. Pageant sponsor [[Catalina swimwear|Catalina]] decided to pull their sponsorship off the pageant and create their own competition.<ref>{{cite news|title=There she goes...Miss America Once queen of the airwaves, beauty pageant is left homeless|publisher=Denver Post|date=2005-10-11|first=Jenny|last=Deam|page=F01}}</ref> Other owners have included a subsidiary of [[Gulf+Western]] Industries, [[ITT Corporation]], and [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf+Western Industries announces reorganization plan|publisher=PR Newswire|date=1985-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump buys Miss Universe, two other beauty pageants |publisher=The Globe and Mail|last=Associated Press|date=1996-10-24|page=B14}}</ref>\n\nThe first Miss USA and Miss Universe pageants were held concurrently in [[Long Beach, California]] in 1952; the first Miss USA winner was [[Miss New York USA]] [[Jackie Loughery]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Long Beach, Calif., Consultant Coaches Beauty Contestants |publisher=Press-Telegram|date=1999-05-28|last=Colon |first=Marisa}}</ref> There were thirty delegates in the first year of competition, and many states did not compete every year during the first two decades of the pageant's history. From the 1970s, each state and the District of Columbia have sent a delegate each year. [[Miss Alaska USA|Alaska]] first competed in 1959 and [[Miss Hawaii USA|Hawaii]] in 1960. Both had competed at Miss Universe until this time.\n\nThe pageant aired on [[CBS]] from [[1963 in television|1963]] until [[2002 in television|2002]], and for many years was known for having a CBS game show host as pageant host. [[John Charles Daly]] hosted the show from 1963\u20131966, [[Bob Barker]] from 1967 (he was not a regular for the CBS network until 1972 when he became host of ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'' which he hosted until 2007) until 1987 (at which point he quit in a dispute over [[fur coat]]s), [[Alan Thicke]] in 1988, [[Dick Clark]] from 1989 to 1993, and [[Bob Goen]] from 1994 to 1996. The show's highest ratings were in the early 1980s, when it regularly topped the Nielsen ratings.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. pulchritude tops TV charts |publisher=The Globe and Mail|date=1980-05-21|last=Associated Press|page=P15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pageant tops Nielsen ratings  |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=1982-05-19|last=Associated Press|page=P15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Beauty pageant most-watched show|publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=1983-05-18 |last=Associated Press|page=P15}}</ref> Viewership dropped sharply from the 1990s to the 2000s, from an estimated viewership of 20 million to an average of 7 million from 2000\u20132001.<ref>{{cite news|title=There She Goes: Pageants Move to NBC|work=The Washington Post|date=2002-06-22|last=de Moraes |first=Lisa}}</ref> In 2002, owner [[Donald Trump]] brokered a new deal with [[NBC]], giving them half-ownership of the Miss USA, Miss Universe and Miss Teen USA and moving them to NBC on an initial five-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trump moves pageants from CBS to NBC|publisher=St. Petersburg Times|date=2002-06-22|page=2B}}</ref> The pageants were first shown on NBC in 2003.\n\nHistorically, the winner of the Miss USA title represented the U.S. in its sister pageant Miss Universe. Since its inception, eight Miss USA titleholders have gone on to win Miss Universe. In the mid-1960s, the organization established a rule that when a Miss USA wins the [[Miss Universe]] title, the first runner-up assumes the Miss USA title for the remainder of the year. This occurred in 1980, 1995, 1997, and 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=News anchor shuns beauty queen past |publisher=St. Petersburg Times|date=1989-10-27|first=Janis|last=Froelich|page=1D}}</ref><ref name=\"sherwood\">{{cite news|title= USA Sherwood |agency=Associated Press|date=1997-05-18}}</ref> In 1967, the first runner-up Susan Bradley of California declined the title and the crown went to the second runner-up [[Cheryl Patton]] of [[Florida]]. The only instance when a first runner-up assumed the title of Miss USA prior to this period was in 1957, when [[Mary Leona Gage]] of [[Maryland]] resigned after it was discovered she was married.<ref>{{cite news|title=Are Trump's Beauties at Home With the Camera? They'll Have to Be|publisher=Washington Post|date=2007-06-21|last=de Moraes |first=Lisa|page=C07}}</ref>\n\nThe winner is assigned a one-year contract with the Miss Universe Organization, traveling across the United States, and in some cases overseas, to spread messages about their chosen causes. Aside from the job, the winner also receives a cash allowance for her entire reign, a modelling portfolio, beauty products, clothes, shoes, as well as styling, healthcare, and fitness services by different sponsors of the pageant. She also gains exclusive access to events such as fashion shows and opening galas, as well as access to casting calls and modeling opportunities throughout New York City. When Donald Trump owned the pageant, the winner was given the use of a Trump Place apartment in New York City during her reign, which she shared with the Miss Universe and Miss Teen USA titleholders. If the winner, for any reason, cannot fulfill her duties as Miss USA, including if she wins the title of Miss Universe, the 1st runner-up takes over.\n\n{{see also|Miss USA 2015#Controversy}}\nIn late-June 2015, both NBC and Spanish-language network [[Univision]] (which was to begin a new five-year contract for Spanish rights) announced that they would cut their ties with Donald Trump and the Miss Universe Organization in response to remarks Trump made relating to undocumented immigrants during the launch of his [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 U.S. presidential campaign]]. Trump threatened to sue both companies over the decision; on June 30, 2015, Trump sued Univision for [[defamation]] and [[breach of contract]].<ref name=deadline-nbcdone>{{cite web|title=NBC: Done With Donald Trump, Miss USA, Miss Universe \u2013 Update |url=http://deadline.com/2015/06/nbc-donald-trump-cancels-miss-usa-miss-universe-1201461913/|website=Deadline|accessdate=1 July 2015|date=2015-06-29}}</ref><ref name=deadline-unilawsuit>{{cite web |title=Donald Trump Hits Univision With $500M Miss USA Lawsuit, Network Calls It \"Ridiculous\" \u2013 Update|url=http://deadline.com/2015/06/donald-trump-univision-lawsuit-miss-usa-1201464957/ |website=Deadline|accessdate=1 July 2015|date=2015-06-30 }}</ref> In February 2016, Donald Trump and Univision reached a settlement ending the litigation. The terms of the settlement remain confidential, but included an agreement for Trump to buy back NBCUniversal's stake in the MUO.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/739184/donald-trump-and-univision-reach-settlement-surrounding-miss-usa-pageant|title=Donald Trump & Univision Reach Settlement Surrounding Miss USA Pageant|website=E! Online|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-03|date=2016-02-11}}</ref><ref name=sale/>\n\nAfter losing its television partners, it was announced that Miss USA 2015 would be [[webcast|streamed]] on the pageant's website. Shortly before the pageant, [[Reelz Channel]] announced that it would broadcast Miss USA 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mashable.com/2015/07/02/miss-usa-reelz/|title=Miss USA will air on TV after all|last=Busis|first=Hillary|work=Mashable|access-date=2017-10-30|language=en}}</ref><ref name=deadline-missusawebcast>{{cite web|title=Miss USA To Be Streamed After NBC And Pageant Co-Hosts Bail|url=http://deadline.com/2015/06/miss-usa-donald-trump-nbc-cancels-univision-1201464497/|website=Deadline|accessdate=1 July 2015|date=2015-06-30}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, [[IMG (company)|IMG]] bought the Miss Universe Organization for an undisclosed amount. The company had previously been involved in licensing and production for the events. The following month, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] announced that it had acquired the U.S. television rights to Miss USA and Miss Universe beginning with [[Miss Universe 2015]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/miss-universe-pageant-fox-1201628887/|title=Miss Universe Pageant Moving to Fox in December|last=Kissell|first=Rick|date=2015-10-28|work=Variety|access-date=2017-10-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=sale>{{cite web|title=WME/IMG Acquires Miss Universe Organization From Donald Trump |url=https://variety.com/2015/biz/news/donald-trump-miss-universe-wmeimg-acquisition-1201592910/|accessdate=17 October 2016|date=2015-09-14}}</ref>\n\n==Competition==\nThe modern pageant consists of a preliminary competition held a week before the pageant when all contestants are judged in swimsuit, gown, and interview competitions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beauty business \u2013 as usual;Miss USA contest fights the blemishes |work=USA Today|date=1988-03-01|page=01D}}</ref>\n\n==State competitions==\n[[File:Miss Minnesota USA 2018, and Miss Mississippi USA 2018.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kalie Wright]], [[Miss Minnesota USA]] 2018, and Laine Mansour, [[Miss Mississippi USA]] 2018, at [[Barksdale Air Force Base]]]]\n\nEvery year, each state holds a preliminary competition to choose their delegate for the Miss USA pageant. In some states (such as [[Miss Texas USA|Texas]] and [[Miss Florida USA|Florida]]), local pageants are also held to determine delegates for the state competition. The state winners hold the title \"Miss (State) USA\" for the year of their reign.\n\nThe most successful state is Texas, which has had the most semi-finalists and winners, including five consecutive Miss USA titleholders during the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pair who groomed beauty queens fired as Miss Texas USA directors |publisher=The Dallas Morning News|page=29A|date=1991-03-27|last=Associated press}}</ref> Other successful states include [[Miss California USA|California]], [[Miss New York USA|New York]], [[Miss Alabama USA|Alabama]], [[Miss Tennessee USA|Tennessee]], and [[Miss South Carolina USA|South Carolina]]. The least successful states are [[Miss Delaware USA|Delaware]], placing only once in 2015; [[Miss Montana USA|Montana]], which has not placed since the 1950s; and [[Miss Wyoming USA|Wyoming]], which gained only its second placement in 2010. The only state which has produced more than one Miss Universe is [[Miss South Carolina USA|South Carolina]].\n\nThe [[Miss Universe Organization]] licenses out the state pageants to pageant directors, who in some cases are responsible for more than one state. The directorial groups are the following: \n*RPM Productions ([[Miss Alabama USA|Alabama]], [[Miss Louisiana USA|Louisiana]], [[Miss North Carolina USA|North Carolina]], [[Miss South Carolina USA|South Carolina]])\n*Vanbros and Associates ([[Miss Arkansas USA|Arkansas]], [[Miss Illinois USA|Illinois]], [[Miss Kansas USA|Kansas]], [[Miss Missouri USA|Missouri]], [[Miss Nebraska USA|Nebraska]], [[Miss Oklahoma USA|Oklahoma]])\n*Future Productions ([[Miss Colorado USA|Colorado]], [[Miss Iowa USA|Iowa]], [[Miss Minnesota USA|Minnesota]], [[Miss North Dakota USA|North Dakota]], [[Miss South Dakota USA|South Dakota]], [[Miss Wisconsin USA|Wisconsin]], [[Miss Wyoming USA|Wyoming]])\n*Pageant Associates ([[Miss Indiana USA|Indiana]], [[Miss Pennsylvania USA|Pennsylvania]], [[Miss West Virginia USA|West Virginia]])\n*Pageants NW Productions ([[Miss Idaho USA|Idaho]], [[Miss Montana USA|Montana]], [[Miss Oregon USA|Oregon]], [[Miss Washington USA|Washington]])\n*Crystal Group ([[Miss Texas USA|Texas]])\n*Greenwood Productions ([[Miss Georgia USA|Georgia]], [[Miss Mississippi USA|Mississippi]], [[Miss Tennessee USA|Tennessee]])\n*D&D Productions ([[Miss Maryland USA|Maryland]], [[Miss New Jersey USA|New Jersey]], [[Miss New York USA|New York]], [[Miss Rhode Island USA|Rhode Island]])\n*Proctor Productions ([[Miss Kentucky USA|Kentucky]], [[Miss Michigan USA|Michigan]], [[Miss Ohio USA|Ohio]])\n*Casting Crown Productions ([[Miss Arizona USA|Arizona]])\n*Smoak Productions ([[Miss Nevada USA|Nevada]], [[Miss Utah USA|Utah]])\n*Nice & Wonderful Productions ([[Miss District of Columbia USA|District of Columbia]], [[Miss Virginia USA|Virginia]])\n*The Clemente Organization ([[Miss Maine USA|Maine]], [[Miss Massachusetts USA|Massachusetts]])\n*Garness Productions ([[Miss Alaska USA|Alaska]])\n*New Media Productions ([[Miss Hawaii USA|Hawaii]])\n*CW Productions ([[Miss Delaware USA|Delaware]])\n*Laura's Productions ([[Miss New Mexico USA|New Mexico]])\n*Ewald Productions ([[Miss Connecticut USA|Connecticut]])\n*GDB Theatre and Pageant Productions ([[Miss New Hampshire USA|New Hampshire]], [[Miss Vermont USA|Vermont]])\n\n[[Miss California USA|California]] and [[Miss Florida USA|Florida]] are vacant as they seek with new directorship in the future.\n\n==Winners==\nThe oldest woman to win Miss USA is [[Miss USA 2019]], [[Cheslie Kryst]] of [[North Carolina]], at 28 years old and 4 days. [[Miss USA 2015]], [[Olivia Jordan]], of [[Oklahoma]] is the only Miss USA winner to compete in two major international pageants: [[Miss Universe]] and [[Miss World]]. The tallest Miss USA is [[Miss USA 2012]], [[Nana Meriwether]], of [[Maryland]] at 6 feet and 1 inch (185&nbsp;cm).\n\nThe first Asian-American woman to win Miss USA was [[Macel Wilson]] of [[Hawaii]] in 1962; the first Hispanic woman was [[Laura Martinez-Herring]] of [[Texas]] in 1985; the first African-American, [[Carole Gist]] of [[Michigan]] in 1990;<ref>{{cite news|title='Royalty' Happy Overseas |publisher=Albuquerque Journal|date=2001-05-16|page=D2}}</ref> and the first Muslim Miss USA was [[Rima Fakih]] of [[Michigan]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last=Knowles |first=David |url=http://trueslant.com/davidknowles/2010/05/17/rima-fakih-first-arab-american-miss-usa/ |title=Rima Fakih, First Muslim Miss USA - David Knowles - Paradigms Lost |publisher=True/Slant |date=2010-05-17 |accessdate=2012-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008135852/http://trueslant.com/davidknowles/2010/05/17/rima-fakih-first-arab-american-miss-usa/ |archivedate=2012-10-08 }}</ref>\n\nThough no woman has ever won both titles outright, [[Brandi Sherwood]] of [[Idaho]] is the only woman to have held both the Miss Teen USA and Miss USA titles. She was [[Miss Idaho Teen USA]], [[Miss Teen USA]] 1989, [[Miss Idaho USA]] 1997, first runner-up at [[Miss USA 1997]], and in May 1997 assumed the Miss USA title after [[Brook Mahealani Lee|Brook Lee]] of [[Hawaii]] won the Miss Universe pageant.<ref name=\"sherwood\" /> Ten other Miss USA titleholders have also previously competed at [[Miss Teen USA]]. These include:\n\n*'''[[Shanna Moakler]]''' (1995, [[Miss Rhode Island Teen USA]] 1992)\n*'''[[Ali Landry]]''' (1996, [[Miss Louisiana Teen USA]] 1990)\n*'''[[Kimberly Pressler]]''' (1999, [[Miss New York Teen USA]] 1994)\n*'''[[Lynnette Cole]]''' (2000, [[Miss Tennessee Teen USA]] 1995)\n*'''[[Susie Castillo]]''' (2003, [[Miss Massachusetts Teen USA]] 1998)\n*'''[[Chelsea Cooley]]''' (2005, [[Miss North Carolina Teen USA]] 2000)\n*'''[[Tara Conner]]''' (2006, [[Miss Kentucky Teen USA]] 2002)\n*'''[[Rachel Smith]]''' (2007, [[Miss Tennessee Teen USA]] 2002)\n*'''[[Alyssa Campanella]]''' (2011, [[Miss New Jersey Teen USA]] 2007)\n*'''[[Sarah Rose Summers]]''' (2018, [[Miss Nebraska Teen USA]] 2012)\n\nFive Miss USA titleholders have also competed at [[Miss America]]. These included: [[Miriam Stevenson]], [[Carlene King Johnson]] and [[Carol Morris]] (1954\u20131956), [[Mai Shanley]] (1984), and [[Shandi Finnessey]] (2004). Shandi Finnessey, Miss USA 2004 and [[Miss Missouri]] 2002 won a preliminary evening gown award at [[Miss America 2003]]. Also, Miriam Stevenson placed in the top 10 at [[Miss America 1954]] as [[Miss South Carolina]] 1953.\n\nMany Miss USA winners have gone to pursue careers in the [[entertainment]] industry. Those who have been successful in the industry include [[Summer Bartholomew]], [[Deborah Shelton]], [[Laura Harring|Laura Martinez-Herring]], [[Kelli McCarty]], [[Shanna Moakler]], [[Lu Parker|Frances Parker]], [[Ali Landry]], [[Kenya Moore]], [[Brandi Sherwood]], [[Kimberly Pressler]], [[Susie Castillo]], [[Shandi Finnessey]], [[Rachel Smith]], and [[Crystle Stewart]].\n\n==Miss USA and runner-ups==\n{{For|full list and details|List of Miss USA titleholders}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"5\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #FFFFFF; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\" |\n|- style=\"